entry.title: [MemoryCache] Add simple LRU based strong reference cache
entry.content:
- Introduce a bounded LRU based on a LinkedListHashSet. The head contains the item to evict first, and the tail has the most recently accessed item. The total size is bounded by a finch field trial flag,

so any increase in PMF from previous studies should be addressed.

- Remove kMemoryCacheStrongReferenceSingleUnload feature. All pages

was shown to be more useful.

- Introduce kResourceFetcherStoresStrongReferences feature. So we can

see if the bounded LRU is good enough instead of storing all references on the ResourceFetchers.

- Blink.MemoryCache.RevalidationPolicy.* counts were previously

counted for non-main thread loads which was incorrect since the

MemoryCache does not apply to non-main threads so exclude them from

the count



Design doc: https://docs.google.com/document/d/1MriQnOp2oHkqHyWriiPxXand_0c3J0CprtL1GFAUrkA/edit

entry.title: Remove 1 overload of deprecated `base::Hash` function.
entry.content:
This CL replaces the callers of the removed overload with calls to

either `base::FastHash` or `base::PersistentHash`:



* `base/hash/hash_unittest.cc` - calling `PersistentHash` to preserve

the old behavior (`Hash` forwards to `PersistentHash`).

* `components/services/heap_profiling/allocation.cc` - calling

`FastHash`. `AllocationSite::Hash` is used as a hasher of

`std::unordered_map`.

* `components/viz/service/display/overlay_candidate_factory.cc` -

calling `FastHash`:

entry.title: Implement "json" fetch destination for JSON module scripts
entry.content:
This patch adds a new `json` fetch destination [fetch-spec-pr], that has

the following characteristics:

- it implies the `Accept: application/json,*/*;q=0.5` HTTP header;

- it uses the `connect-src` CSP directive [csp-spec-pr].



This new destination is used when fetching JSON module scripts, using

`import ... from "/data" with { type: "json" }` [html-spec-pr].

https://crrev.com/c/4949956 implements a similar change for CSS module

scripts, but their implementation is simpler because the `style`

destination already exists.



This patch passes all the relevant WPT tests [wpt-pr] (when using

--js-flags="--harmony_import_attributes), although I had to run them

manually because they have not been merged yet.



This patch does not add support for ``,

which is also introduced by the linked fetch and HTML spec changes.



[fetch-spec-pr]: https://github.com/whatwg/fetch/pull/1691

[csp-spec-pr]: https://github.com/w3c/webappsec-csp/pull/611

[html-spec-pr]: https://github.com/whatwg/html/pull/9486

[wpt-pr]: https://github.com/web-platform-tests/wpt/pull/41665

entry.title: Support typing echo with IME
entry.content:
This adds a support of typing with IME in ChromeVox.



There are a few specific input field changes that wasn't handled before

this change, which are essential for supporting typing with IME:

1. Simultaneous characters removal and addition just before the cursor.

- This can happen when typing CJKV.

- This may not make any selection change events.

2. Moving cursor backward together with value change in the jumped

range.

- This happens when a user starts choosing a candidate from a

candidate window.



This is a part of http://go/chromevox-jp-ime.

entry.content:

closing. If so, leave the view hierarchy clean up to the native

widget instead of manually deleting the view since it will refresh

the next time the glanceables is opened.

entry.title: Fix install timestamp of command-line extensions in telemetry reports
entry.content:
The extension telemetry service reports the install timestamp of a

command-line extension as 0. The 0 value indicates that the

extension is not actually installed because command-line loads

are disabled for Enhanced Safe Browsing (ESB) opted-in users.



This CL fixes an edge-case where the command-line extension had

previously been installed, for example when ESB was disabled. When

ESB is enabled, the telemetry service reported this previous install

timestamp instead of 0. This CL ensures that the service reports an

install timestamp of 0 always.

entry.title: [grid] Downgrade flex fraction logic to floats (instead of doubles).
entry.content:
Previously we had a separate struct for representing fr-units called

GridLengths. This stored a Length, and then separately a double for

fr units.



In:

https://chromium-review.googlesource.com/c/chromium/src/+/4815886



I merged these two objects, however this left us storing fr's as

floats, but performing operations as doubles. This resulted in sutble

numerical errors when converting between them.



To remove the conversions, use floats within the grid logic instead.



The primary risk of this patch is the loss of precision, however this

seems unlikely in real world usages.

entry.title: Use `span` instead of ptr+len pair as param of `base::Hash` function.
entry.content:
`base::Hash` has the following 2 overloads:



```

BASE_EXPORT uint32_t Hash(const void* data, size_t length);

BASE_EXPORT uint32_t Hash(const std::string& str);

```



This CL replaces the 1st overload with:



```

BASE_EXPORT uint32_t Hash(base::span data);

```



`base::Hash` is a deprecated function that in the long-term should be

replaced with either 1) `base::FastHash` (result can vary when launching

Chrome or tests another time) or 2) `base::PersistentHash` (same result

every time forever). Deprecation is tracked in

https://crbug.com/1025358. To minimize risk and amount of changes this

CL preserves the old behavior (i.e. continues to use the deprecated

`base::Hash`) and the removal will be attempted in a separate WIP CL at

https://crrev.com/c/5206108.

entry.title: [MFVEA,VP9]unblock client going up for higher temporal layers encoding
entry.content:
1. Currently, the frame dependency of VP9 temporal encoding on Intel

platform diverged from WebRTC SVC spec, a T1 frame may ref the previous

T1 frame, leads to not all T0 frame can be marked as up-switch which

block client going up for higher temporal layers from base layer. Since

the frame dependency follows a deterministic pattern, we can pick out

the T0 frame meets the requirements and mark it as up-switch.

entry.title: Update PrintingContext job_id API
entry.content:
The PrintingContext class has included a comment that the job_id will

be zero if no jobs are active. This field has not properly honored

that API description. The field is not initialized to a default value,

and thus starts with a garbage value. Additionally, it only ever gets

a real job ID value for the ChromeOS platform, which is needed by that

platform's extra CUPS management logic.



Correct the handling of `job_id_` such that it is initialized to zero

for all platforms. Further update the comments to clarify when the

field could be non-zero.



This is a simpler change at this time than making the `job_id_` field be

ChromeOS-only. It also prepares for the changes to the browser tests

in CL https://crrev.com/c/5208090 (which do not currently run for

ChromeOS) to demonstrate a problem for job ID handling when the

out-of-process print drivers feature is enabled.

entry.title: Propagate PrintingContext job ID from service back to browser
entry.content:
The PrintingContext job ID can be updated at the start of making system

calls to print a document. This job ID is used when printing has

completed, where it is passed along the print management notification

stack.



The actual value of the job ID is currently irrelevant for all

platforms except ChromeOS. On ChromeOS, the ID is used for some

further print job management tracking. Without a valid ID that matches

what was determined at the start of printing, that platform will report

the job as "lost", even if the document was actually able to be printed.



When the out-of-process print drivers feature is enabled, setting this

job ID occurs in the PrintBackend service. Since this value was not

previously being passed back to the browser process, OOPPD printing on

ChromeOS would exhibit the lost jobs issue.



Update the interface to return the PrintingContext job ID back to the

browser process, so that the PrintingContext API behaves as expected

for objects that exist in the browser process.

entry.title: Make printing tests track job ID when document completes
entry.content:
Once a print job starts making the system calls to print the document,

the PrintingContext can possibly get a non-zero job ID. Whatever the

ID value is, that is passed along through the print notifications stack

in the browser process. This is of particular importance for ChromeOS,

which uses the job ID value for extra job management.



Update TestPrintingContext to support using a particular job ID once

the NewDocument() call is invoked. Expand the printing tests to use

this and capture the job ID once the document is done. This is used as

part of validation checks, demonstrating that the value is incorrect

when the out-of-process print drivers feature is enabled.

entry.content:
The crash keys say `GetRootWindowBeingDraggedIn()` returns null when

using mouse dragging. They also say the display id returned by the

cursor manger is valid, but fetching the root window associated

returns null. Something similar was seen before in CL:4245998. We will

use a different display getter based on the screen cursor position.



Due to no longer using the cursor manager, we don't need to call

`OveviewWindowDragController` functions directly nor set the display

to the cursor manager every time we drag to another display.

entry.content:
There's no point in reporintg deprecated feature use when converting

a native dictionary to JS, since it does not indicate that the page

is actually using the property, only that we're providing it. It would

have made sense if we were to provide an accessor in this case, but this

is not how it is implemented, and we don't have actual usage of

non-trivial and already used in optimization_guide, let's not bother

replicating it for this WebUI.



Note that the WebUI already effectively ignores the safety model

by opting out of its use when executing the main model, but

because the WebUI impl still provides the necessary assets, the

service still attempts to load the model. This change prevents

crashing the service process when said assets have unexpected

structure.



We can revisit this decision if later we want to add explicit support

for inspecting safety model behavior through on-device-internals.

entry.title: [Windows] Overwrite existing CurrentVersion symlink
entry.content:
We've had reports that installing a new Windows host package on a

Windows machine which is set to run PowerShell in a constrained

language mode results in a broken CurrentVersion link.



The reason is that this mode prevents the delete action from working

properly and the MSI does not write over the previous symlink

unless the '-Force' argument is provided.



We could consider changing the command line we use to delete the

symlink but the behavior would then be to recursively delete the

target dir as well which we'd need to make sure we don't do for

maintenance operations.



A simpler fix is to just provide the -Force arg when creating the

symlink which feels like something we'd want anyway.
